# Normalize line endings to LF in the repository AND in the working tree.
#
# This project's QA method depends on byte-level comparison: the drift ledgers in
# AUDIT-FINDINGS §16.3 and the `_detail` byte-equality gate in §18.2 both assert that
# specific field values and generated artifacts are byte-identical to a baseline.
#
# The working tree at first commit was MIXED: the row modules, compliance-atlas.html,
# compliance-atlas.json, and the reference snapshots were CRLF (Python's text-mode
# write on Windows emits \r\n); assemble.py, common.py, template.html, and the docs
# were LF. The global setting is core.autocrlf=true, so without a rule here the repo
# would inherit that inconsistency permanently and produce noisy, meaningless diffs.
#
# `eol=lf` normalizes on check-in and check-out, so the repository holds LF
# throughout. A rebuild on Windows re-emits CRLF in the working tree, which check-in
# normalization then folds back to LF — so a rebuild that changes no content shows no
# diff. This is what makes `git diff` usable as a drift check alongside the existing
# ledgers.
#
# Note this DOES change the on-disk line endings of the generated artifacts at the
# next checkout. That is safe: the drift gates compare parsed JSON field values, not
# raw file bytes, and both artifacts are regenerable from build/.

* text=auto eol=lf

# Explicit: build inputs and outputs stay LF.
*.py    text eol=lf
*.html  text eol=lf
*.json  text eol=lf
*.md    text eol=lf
*.txt   text eol=lf
*.xml   text eol=lf

# Binary — never touch, never diff as text.
*.pdf   binary
*.xlsx  binary
*.png   binary
*.jpg   binary
